<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Accuses Muslims of Using Chlorine in Central Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101140094 Hamburg DPA in German 1259 GMT 11 Jan 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1101140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn/Zagreb (DPA) -- Croatian President Franjo 
Tudjman today accused the Muslims of using chlorine gas shells 
in the fighting in central Bosnia. Following the departure of 
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic, with whom Tudjman had held 
talks at a two-day conference in Bonn, Tudjman also accused the 
Muslims of continued offensives. However, he described the 
Bosnia-Croatian conference at the Petersberg government guest 
house as useful. 
  Even after Tudjman's remarks, it remained unclear whether 
there would be a cease-fire in central Bosnia. Izetbegovic said 
yesterday evening on ZDF [Second German Television Channel] that 
"no major results" had been achieved. Both presidents are now 
preparing for a new round of talks on 18 January in Geneva, this 
time involving all warring parties from the conference on former 
Yugoslavia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

