<H3> <TI>   Danish Deputies Oppose Handover of al-Jihad Terrorists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2401105694 Cairo AL-AHALI in Arabic 19 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC2401105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-AHALI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Tharwat Shalabi] </F>
  [Text] AL-AHALI has learned that several terrorist leaders 
residing abroad will be handed over to the Egyptian authorities 
in the near future in line with agreements recently signed with 
several Arab and other foreign countries. 
  Interior Minister Major General Hasan al-Alfi worked hard to 
conclude the agreements with these countries during a recent 
Arab interior ministers' conference in Tunisia. The countries 
with whom agreements were signed include a neighboring country, 
a non-neighboring country that is suffering internal conflicts, 
and a major Gulf country, which set the condition that the 
agreement must not be made public in order to avoid terrorist 
reprisals! 
  Following security negotiations with Egypt, Denmark arrested 
Tal'at Fu'ad Qasim, the most prominent al-Jihad leader abroad, 
and several other leading figures of that organization. Some 
Danish parliamentarians are opposing their being handed over to 
Egypt, however, on the grounds that Egyptian law provides for 
the death penalty, which these parliamentarians regard as 
violating human rights. 
  Egyptian security departments have sent high-level 
delegations to Afghanistan and Pakistan to sign similar 
agreements. Domestic events in Afghanistan have held up talks 
with that country. 

</TEXT>

