<H3> <TI>   Italians in Egypt Advised To Be `Vigilant and Apply Caution' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0402114994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2005 GMT 3 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BR0402114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Advice to Italians Here: Caution, </F>
Good Sense"] 
  [Text] Cairo, 3 Feb (ANSA) -- European embassies in Cairo 
today urged their nationals to exercise vigilance but avoid 
alarm as a spokesman for the Italian Embassy advised Italians in 
Egypt to be vigilant and apply caution and good sense following 
a warning of attacks on foreigners issued by a radical Islamic 
group. 
  This spokesman said the embassy was not considering 
emergency 
measures "either for the community or for enterprises" as a 
result of the group's threat of "extremely ferocious and strong" 
operations against foreign tourists and investors issued 
Wednesday [2 February] after seven of the Islamic militants were 
killed in a police raid on an apartment in Cairo. "Caution and 
good sense mean not going into areas and quarters which are 
notoriously dangerous, avoiding provocative conduct and 
clothing, and taking account that Ramadan, the Muslim month of 
fasting, is about to begin," said the embassy spokesman to the 
Italian news agency ANSA. 
  Also explained was that checks run on visitors to the 
diplomatic representation installed long ago, following earlier 
threats of this nature, were being kept in place. 
  The president of the Italian Chamber of Commerce in Cairo, 
Cesare d'Ippolito, said he had witnessed no panic among Italian 
businessmen, who had all been informed of the statement sent out 
by the Islamic group. 

</TEXT>

