<F P=101> YEMEN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Claims State `Collaborating With Terrorists' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202070194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2130 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0202070194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Feb (MENA)--Yemeni Prime Minister Haydar 
Abu-Bakr al-'Attas has revealed wide differences among the 
parties competing for authority in his country. He accused the 
political powers involved in the ruling process of adopting a 
harsh, centralized, and backward approach to running the 
country's affairs. He said this confirms that there is no desire 
to unify institutions, but rather to maintain the status quo. 
  In an interview with AL-AHRAM to be published on 2 February, 
al-'Attas said he rejected an offer by Yemeni President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih to join the General People's Congress to avoid 
further division within the Yemeni Socialist Party. 
  Al-'Attas affirmed that there are military movements in the 
two sections of Yemen, particularly after the suspension of all 
projects to rebuild, restructure, and unite the Armed Forces 
since the declaration of unity on 22 May. 
  The Yemeni prime minister accused the state of collaborating 
with terrorists to strike at rival political forces in the local 
arena. He noted that the terrorist elements in Yemen are being 
used in operations at home and abroad. 
  Asked when he would return to Sanaa, al-'Attas said: Soon, 
once we reach full agreement on the security arrangements and 
the legal and constitutional guarantees that aim to rearrange 
affairs and establish peace and stability in Yemen. 

</TEXT>

